Started this concept for fun last summer, went to a few seminars in between then and now, traveled, exchanged knowledge with other artists, learned a lot, erased a lot, redrew a lot. I wanted it to be a deeply intentional piece so I only worked on it when I felt inspired to work on it. Which as a tattoo artist, is rare. We always have deadlines, strict schedules, drawings that need to be finished by appointment day— whether we feel inspired to finish or not. This piece has been a very slow-paced token of growth and patience, over what has been a wildly transformative year for me. Anywayyyy, I was finally happy with it and made some prints. They’re 12x18” giclee prints on 110lb watercolor paper. Limited quantities are available on the sh0p site (in b!0) or stop by the sh0p to grab one! Thanks for looking ♥️
.

1. Shop for an artist by portfolio. Research. Don’t choose an artist solely based on their price, their social media presence or just because “they did your friend’s tattoo”. Take all of these into consideration but first and foremost, see if their portfolio/style matches the style you want. You wouldn’t seek out a realism artist for an illustrative piece. Artists have different strengths and aren’t one-size fits all.
2. Come prepared! — arrive well-hydrated with a good nights rest and have a breakfast with protein. Bring a sweatshirt in case the AC is blasting (summer thangs), a snack, headphones/something to entertain yourself! No one wants to be in pain AND uncomfortable. 
3. Don’t make dire plans for immediately after your appointment… sometimes tattoos take longer than expected due to a LOT of physical factors. Leave some flexibility in your schedule so your artist isn’t rushed.
4. Speak up if something doesn’t feel right, if you’d prefer an aspect of the design changed (within reason), you’d like the stencil moved, etc. Artists should be kind and understanding of these requests. Our goal is for you to be as stoked on your tattoo as we are!
#newtattoo #tattooartist #learnontiktok #tattoo #tattooshop

1. Tattoos can be easier to heal in the colder months because it’s easier to avoid the sun, swimming, the beach, or other outdoor activities that are going to be an infection risk. Tattoos are an open wound after all, so avoiding harsh UV rays and bacteria from the outdoors is key.
2. Having appointments in the darker months gives you something to look forward to when that seasonal depression hits. Having an on-going large scale project or a few scattered sessions will boost that will to live 📈😌 Plus tattoos are a great way to stay grounded within your body and receive a confidence boost.
3. Tattoos are easier to hide in the colder months (if your loved ones need to be eased into the idea of tattoos or you’re not ready to reveal it quite yet). You don’t owe anyone an explanation for what you choose to do with your body but sometimes, you just don’t feel like having that conversation yet. Do it when you’re ready.
4. It will look nice and settled by the time spring rolls around. Tattoos typically heal within 2-3 weeks but the tattoo will continue to “settle” in your skin for up to a few months. Settling refers to when the skin fully grows back and is no longer thin or shiny over your tattoo. Lines spread slightly, it begins to look a little more “lived in” and more true to what it will look like for years to come. 
.
.

1. The learning curve can’t be rushed. Everyone’s in a race to be the best, the fastest. For the beginning of my career, I was under the impression that working 3x harder = improving 3x faster. Of course, there’s truth to the 10,000 hour rule or that some will improve extraordinarily fast but authentic improvement comes from seeing your work 1, 3, 5+ years healed and adjusting your technique accordingly along the way. That process can’t be rushed.
2. Breaks really ARE that important. I used to not take a break during my day (again, because thinking working 3x harder = getting 3x better) but it’s so beneficial to readjust, eat, stretch, etc. Whether it’s taking a 5 minute break to readjust your eyes during a tattoo, or a whole ass hiatus. Expecting inspiration to come to you abundantly and constantly is unrealistic. Part of what makes us human and what makes art impactful, is the ebb and flow. 
3. Set boundaries early on and practice enforcing them. Setting boundaries in tattooing looks like: Sticking to your deposit policies. Not letting people take advantage of you. Not overbooking. Letting clients know if their behavior makes you uncomfortable. Even saying no the pieces you don’t have the skills to accomplish. Sometimes you’ll need to explain why you’re setting that boundary— rarely is anyone receptive of a “no because I said so”. Open communication builds trust with clients and that trust is the foundation of body art.
4. Invest in your clients. Be extra. Buy quality tattoo supplies. Provide complimentary snacks, drinks, and comforts for them. Invest in a streamlined form of communication (like an assistant or user-friendly scheduling system). Invest in their lives by making conversation and getting to know them (this should be bare minimum and go without saying tbh). These things are what make the difference between an average tattoo experience and a returning-client tattoo experience.
5. Never get too comfortable. Challenge yourself as often as you can bare. Network with other artists. Travel. This is where the growth and magic really happens. 
6. Stay humble.

I’m a few days late here but in the spirit of ~The Day of Thanks~ I wanted to say a little thank you to all of you. Whether you’re a regular client, a fellow artist or just a follower from wayyy far away, your support means everything. It’s been about a year since I started the process of opening my own studio and this past year has absolutely been the most rewarding and transformative yet. Finally being in a space where I can thrive, make it a home, nest and decorate, run things the way we think best, and so on, is an indescribable feeling of freedom that has catapulted my growth, creativity and gratitude immensely. Even 6 years into this craft, everyday I think to myself about how cool it is that people (especially strangers) have so much trust in me to mark their bodies with my drawings forever?!? Some days are than more challenging than others, even when you think you’ve seen it all but this craft is an absolute dream. I feel so fortunate everyday for y’all allowing me the opportunity to do what I do. Having said that, my books open this Friday 12/1 for February & March so if you’d like to come in, fill out an inquiry then! I can’t wait to see what this new year of tattooing brings— thank you, thank you 🥹🫶 
.
.

One whole year of Take Heart. Here’s a glimpse into what the last year has brought. What you don’t see is the endless troubleshooting, learning curves, mistakes, paperwork, IKEA-furniture-mental-breakdowns, the painting walls and ceilings, boundary setting, body aches, dirty hands, curating artwork and antiquing trips. Many long days and cold nights spent putting everything together with family and friends in a snow storm or two. I’m not sure I believe in karma but I do think the universe reciprocates good things when you put in hard work, kindness and genuine intentions. 
Most tattooers feel like outsiders so being overly independent has always come a lil too natural to me. This year I’ve learned that it really does take a village to accomplish big things and that allowing people to help in your process is so important. This year has taught me that whether you’re a friend at the other side of the country, a family member I’ve just met, a client or a follower online, we all share surprisingly similar experiences, thoughts and desires. Most people understand you more than you know— and so I’ve never felt more at home and less alone. This year has made me a better artist, partner, friend and tattooer. Thank you to everyone who’s come through our doors and who’s made this lil dream shop possible!
.
